<quantity id="4CE79B052B2CFF8AFC19CAFF5D715982" box="[966,1070,1673,1700]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.18" pageId="6" pageNumber="491" unit="mm" value="21.8">21.8 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA036E02B2DFF8BFFAECCAE59B85FD6" blockId="7.[113,604,216,275]" box="[113,231,216,242]" pageId="7" pageNumber="492">VARIATION</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA036E02B2DFF8BFFAECC8E5B035E35" blockId="7.[113,604,216,275]" box="[113,604,248,275]" pageId="7" pageNumber="492">
The species is only known from the 
<typeStatus id="54A488422B2DFF8BFE29CC8E5B075E35" box="[502,600,248,275]" pageId="7" pageNumber="492">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C305656B2B2DFF8BFFAECD4158595C6B" pageId="7" pageNumber="492" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA036E02B2DFF8BFFAECD41598A5E69" blockId="7.[112,649,311,845]" box="[113,213,311,337]" pageId="7" pageNumber="492">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA036E02B2DFF8BFFAECD2158595C6B" blockId="7.[112,649,311,845]" pageId="7" pageNumber="492">
Due to the colouring it is likely that the specimen is immature. A comparison with the original description (
<bibRefCitation id="EF8E4B112B2DFF8BFED8CDE058E25E97" author="KIMMINS D. E." box="[263,445,406,433]" pageId="7" pageNumber="492" pagination="237 - 250" refId="ref7776" refString="KIMMINS D. E. 1958. - Miss L. E. Cheesman's expedition to New Hebrides, 1955. Orders Odonata, Neuroptera and Trichoptera. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) 6 (9): 237 - 250." type="journal article" year="1958">Kimmins 1958</bibRefCitation>
) reveals that the colouration has lost its intensity over the last 53 years. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8E4B112B2DFF8BFE91CDA35B585ED6" author="KIMMINS D. E." box="[334,519,469,496]" pageId="7" pageNumber="492" pagination="237 - 250" refId="ref7776" refString="KIMMINS D. E. 1958. - Miss L. E. Cheesman's expedition to New Hebrides, 1955. Orders Odonata, Neuroptera and Trichoptera. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) 6 (9): 237 - 250." type="journal article" year="1958">Kimmins (1958)</bibRefCitation>
it could be quite possible that the yellowish-fuscous areas become bluish or greenish during the maturation process. Males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1F4D632B2DFF8BFEEDCE4358CF5D68" authorityName="Ober &amp; Staniczek" authorityYear="2009" box="[306,400,564,590]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Nesobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="492" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bidens" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis id="B96BEAF22B2DFF8BFEEDCE4358CF5D68" box="[306,400,564,590]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="492">V. bidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A25857892B2DFF8BFE48CE4258A65D69" box="[407,505,564,591]" pageId="7" pageNumber="492" rank="species">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be easily distinguished from males of the other two species of the genus by the bidentate apical margins of the superior anal appendages. These appendages appear in the dried specimen in a very upright position, in life, they may be in a more oblique position. The length of the abdomen was stated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8E4B112B2DFF8BFF4BCF6458115C0B" author="KIMMINS D. E." box="[148,334,786,813]" pageId="7" pageNumber="492" pagination="237 - 250" refId="ref7776" refString="KIMMINS D. E. 1958. - Miss L. E. Cheesman's expedition to New Hebrides, 1955. Orders Odonata, Neuroptera and Trichoptera. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) 6 (9): 237 - 250." type="journal article" year="1958">Kimmins (1958)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<quantity id="4CE79B052B2DFF8BFEABCF6458975C0B" box="[372,456,786,813]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="7" pageNumber="492" unit="mm" value="25.0">25 mm</quantity>
, this seems to be a literal error.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
